{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Education |nativename = وزارت آموزش و پرورش ایران |nativename_a = |nativename_r = |logo = Coat of arms of Iran.svg |logo_width = 100px |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = 1964 |preceding1 = |preceding2 = |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction = [[Islamic Republic of Iran]] |headquarters = |employees = |budget = |minister1_name = |minister1_pfo = |minister2_name = |minister2_pfo = |chief1_name = [[Mohammad Bathaei]] |chief1_position = |chief2_name = |chief2_position = |parent_agency = |child1_agency = |child2_agency = |website = [http://medu.ir Official website] |footnotes = }} {{Politics of Iran}}
The '''Ministry of Education''' ({{lang-fa|وزارت آموزش و پرورش ایران}}) established in 1964, is an [[Iran]]ian government body responsible for the oversight of [[K-12 education]] in Iran. Each year, 20% of [[Government of Iran#Public finance and fiscal policy|government spending]] and 5% of GDP goes to education, a higher rate than most other developing countries. 50% of education spending is devoted to secondary education and 21% of the annual state education budget is devoted to the provision of tertiary education.<ref>{{Cite document |last = Nash |first = Jason John |url = http://www.thebusinessyear.com/tby_demo//publications.php?art_id=113&type=sector&sector=healtheducation |last2 = Sasmaz |first2 = Aytng |author2-link = |title = The Business Year 2011: Iran |place = London, U.K. |publisher = The Business Year |origyear = |date = January 2011 |volume = |edition = |chapter = |chapterurl = |page = |pages = 232 |doi = |isbn = 978-1-908180-00-1 |postscript = . }}{{dead link|date=February 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Also [[Shahid Rajaee Teacher Training University]] and [[Farhangian University]] are the university of teacher education and human resource development in Ministry of Education.
